{{Infobox UK legislation |short_title=Arbitration Act 1950 |parliament=Parliament of the United Kingdom |long_title=An Act to consolidate the Arbitration Acts, 1889 to 1934. |statute_book_chapter=c.27 |introduced_by= |territorial_extent=England and Wales |royal_assent=28 July 1950 |commencement= |repeal_date= |amendments=[[Arbitration Act 1979]] |related_legislation= |repealing_legislation= |status= |original_text=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1950/27/pdfs/ukpga_19500027_en.pdf |revised_text= |use_new_UK-LEG=yes |legislation_history= |}} The '''Arbitration Act 1950''' (c.27, 14 Geo. 6) was an [[Acts of Parliament in the United Kingdom|Act]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] that consolidated and amended [[arbitration]] law in [[England and Wales]].
Although the Act has now largely been superseded by the [[Arbitration Act 1996]], Part II of the Act (dealing with the enforcement of non-[[Convention on the Recognition and Enforcement of Foreign Arbitral Awards|New York Convention]] [[arbitral award|awards]]) remains in force.<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1996/23/section/99 Arbitration Act 1996, section 99]</ref> This is principally to preserve the enforcement mechanism for awards made under the (now largely obsolete) [[Geneva Protocol (1924)]].
The main purpose of the Act was to consolidate and rationalise the prior statutes regulating arbitration. However the 1950 Act became increasingly subject to criticism because of the power of the courts to review [[arbitral award|arbitration awards]] under section 21. That section required the [[arbitration tribunal]] to make a "[[Case stated|statement of case]]" on any matter of law which was reviewable by the court. This was unpopular and led to loss of arbitration business in the United Kingdom, and led to the repeal of the provisions under the [[Arbitration Act 1979]].
