{{short description|business model monetizing commercial open-source software}} {{Multiple issues| {{unreliable sources|date=March 2013}} {{cleanup rewrite|date=March 2013}} }} {{Redirect|Open core|the open-source hardware community|OpenCores}} {{broader|Business models for open-source software}} The '''open-core model''' is a [[business model]] for the [[monetization]] of commercially-produced [[open-source software]]. Coined by Andrew Lampitt in 2008,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Phipps|first1=Simon|title=Open Source Strategies for the Enterprise|date=July 2012|publisher=O'Reilly Media|isbn=978-1-4493-4117-6}}</ref> the open-core model primarily involves offering a "core" or [[crippleware|feature-limited]] version of a software product as [[free and open-source software]], while offering "commercial" versions or add-ons as [[proprietary software]].<ref name="Riehle">{{cite conference | first = Dirk | last = Riehle | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Commercial Open Source Business Model | booktitle = Value Creation in e-Business Management | pages = 18–30 | publisher = Springer Verlag | date = 2009 | location = | url = http://dirkriehle.com/publications/2009/the-commercial-open-source-business-model/ | accessdate = | id = }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|first1=Anthony I.|last1=Wasserman|title=How the Internet transformed the software industry|url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s13174-011-0019-x|journal=Journal of Internet Services and Applications |issn= 1867-4828 |pages= 11–22 |volume=2 |issue=1 |doi= 10.1007/s13174-011-0019-x |accessdate= 25 January 2015 |quote= Some companies have only a single version of their software, while others follow an “open core” model, providing a community release of the core version, and offering proprietary premium features using a commercial license. |date=2011}}</ref>
==Controversy== The concept of open-core software has proven to be controversial, as many developers do not consider the business model to be true open-source software. Despite this, open-core models are used by a large number of open-source software companies.<ref name=li-opencore>{{cite web|title=Open Core Debate: The Battle for a Business Model|url=http://www.linuxinsider.com/story/66807.html|publisher=Linux Insider|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref>
==Use of contributor license agreements== Some open-core products require their contributors to sign a [[contributor license agreement]], which either dictates that the copyright of all contributions to the product [[Work for hire|become the property of its owner]], or that the product's owner is given an unlimited, non-exclusive license to use the contributions, but the authors retain copyright ownership. In an open-core scenario, these agreements are typically meant to allow the commercial owner of the product (which in some cases, is ultimately the copyright holder to all of its code, regardless of its original author) to simultaneously market versions of the product under open-source and non-free licenses. This is in contrast with more traditional uses of CLAs, which are meant solely to allow the steward of an open-source project to defend its copyright, or guarantee that the code will only ever be made available under open-source terms, thus protecting it from becoming open core.<ref name=infoworld-mysqlmistake>{{cite web|title=MySQL mistake is a wake-up call on open source ownership|url=http://www.javaworld.com/article/2078812/open-source-tools/mysql-mistake-is-a-wake-up-call-on-open-source-ownership.html|website=InfoWorld|accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://ev.kde.org/announcements/2008-08-22-fsfe-welcomes-fla.php | date = 2008-08-22 | title = FSFE welcomes KDE's adoption of the Fiduciary Licence Agreement (FLA)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gnu.org/prep/maintain/html_node/Copyright-Papers.html | title = 6.1 Copyright Papers | accessdate = 2011-01-03}}</ref>
==Examples== * [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]]'s [[MySQL]] database software is dual-licensed under a proprietary license, and the [[GNU GPL]]; proprietary versions offer additional features and enterprise support plans.<ref name=theh-sqlopencore>{{cite web|title=Open core or dual licensing? The example of MySQL|url=http://www.h-online.com/open/features/Open-core-or-dual-licensing-The-example-of-MySQL-1367824.html|website=The H|accessdate=11 September 2015}}</ref> * [[Eucalyptus (software)|Eucalyptus]], private cloud software, has a proprietary enterprise edition which provides additional features.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/the-startup-that-ticked-off-a-lot-of-people-just-got-30-million-in-funding-2012-4 |title=This Startup That Angered A Lot Of Open Source Fans Just Got $30 Million In Funding |last1=Bort |first1=Julie |date=18 April 2012 |publisher=Business Insider |access-date=19 February 2016 |quote=It was one of the first commercial companies to champion a concept called "open core." }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2231115/opensource-subnet/marten-mickos-says-open-source-doesn-t-have-to-be-fully-open.html |title=Marten Mickos says open source doesn't have to be fully open |last1=Bort |first1=Julie |date=22 June 2010 |publisher=Network World |access-date=19 February 2016 |quote="We deliver a fully functional cloud with Eucalyptus software. You can download it on a GPL v3 license. But, additionally, we provide enterprise features only if you pay for them ... it's open core," he says.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/204092/article.html |title=Eucalyptus Strengthens Its Back End |last1=Jackson |first1=Jacob |publisher=PCWorld |access-date=19 February 2016 |quote=To make money, Eucalyptus Systems uses an open-core business model, offering one version of the software free through an open-source license and selling a commercial version with support and additional features ...}}</ref> * [[GitLab|Gitlab]] CE (Community Edition) is under a [[MIT License|MIT-style]] open source license,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab-ce/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md|title=CONTRIBUTING.md · master · GitLab.org / GitLab Community Edition|website=GitLab|language=en|access-date=2018-06-05}}</ref> while Gitlab EE (Enterprise Edition) is under a [[commercial software|commercial license]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://about.gitlab.com/2014/02/11/gitlab-ee-license-change/|title=GitLab Enterprise Edition license change|date=2014-02-11|work=GitLab|access-date=2018-06-05|language=en}}</ref> *[[Neo4j#Licensing and editions|Neo4j]] CE (Community Edition) is under [[GNU General Public License|GPLv3]], while Neo4j EE (Enterprise Edition) is [[Multi-licensing|dual-licensed]]: [[GNU Affero General Public License|AGPLv3]] and Commercial, allowing clustering and hot backups. * [[Redis]] is under a [[BSD_licenses#3-clause_license_|3-clause BSD]] open source license,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://redis.io/topics/license|title=Redis license and trademark information|website=redis.io|language=en|access-date=2018-08-24}}</ref> while Redis Labs offers Redis Enterprise is under a [[commercial software|commercial license]] which provides additional features including a search engine and JSON support.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://redislabs.com/community/licenses/|title=Licenses|access-date=2018-08-24|language=en}}</ref>
